                h1 Introduction
                p In our previous three articles on <a class="inline-link"aria-label="a link to article on HTML" role="link" href="./html_the_webs_skeleton.html">HTML</a>, <a class="inline-link" aria-label="a link to article on CSS" role="link" href="./css_the_webs_makeup.html">CSS</a>, and <a class="inline-link" aria-label="a lnk to article on JavaScript" role="link" href="./javascript_the_webs_muscles.html">JavaScript</a>, I provided you with a general overview of the three main languages utilized to interface with modern web browsers. In reading this articles, however, you may have noticed that how these three languages interface directly with each other may not be obvious. This is especially true of the article on JavaScript, as there was no manipulation of the Document Object Model using JavaScript.
                p As mentioned in my previous article, JavaScript is a vast subject in its own right. It is my hope that through this series of blog posts that you gain a good introductory understanding of how web pages and web applications come to life. Because JavaScript is a full-fledged programming language, the basic aspects of programming needed to be addressed before diving into how it interfaces directly with the browser's Application Interface (i.e. API).
                h2 The To Do List
                p In preparation for this article, I created a small To Do List Application. Beginner programmers, regardless of the programming language they are learning, are often encouraged to start with building a To Do List Application. The reason for this is because the essential concepts learned while building such an application are easily applied to the majority of real world applications. Specifically, building a To Do List Application teaches you about the basic operations commonly found in many applications. These operations are "Create", "Read", "Update", and "Delete", abbreviated as the acronym, "CRUD". 
                p These correspond roughly to the standard HTTP operations, which will be the subject of a future blog post where this To Do List application is expanded out of just the browser, and is hooked up to a backend server and database. For now, however, this application will be kept on the front end in order to introduce you to how JavaScript specifically interacts with the DOM, and the Browser's key/value API, localStorage.
                p Be aware that this blog article's subject and follow along tutorial assumes you have an introductory understanding of HTML, CSS, and JavaScript. Should you need to brush up on the basics, I encourage you to read up on these subjects in my previous three blog posts. This blog post will dive deeper than the previous three. We will be introducing many new aspects of HTML, CSS, and JavaScript within this article, but hopefully by the end you will have further expanded your knowledge on exactly what's going on under the hood of web applications and web pages. Let's get started.
                h2 The Setup
                p If you simply wish to follow along without writing any code, you can find the source files for the To Do Application <a class="inline-link" aria-label="a link to the source code for the todo app" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" role="link" href="https://www.github.com/tomit4/app_todo">here</a>. To grab the source code, one can simply clone the repository using git from the command line:
                pre
                    code #bash&#10&#10git clone https://github.com/tomit4/app_todo
                p Navigate into the cloned directory and use live-server to start a local version of the application:
                pre
                    code #bash&#10&#10cd app_todo && live-server index.html
                p The output of the command should open up the application in your browser with which you can now start experimenting with the functionality of the To Do App.
                p If, however, you wish to follow along from start to finish, then you'll need to make a directory in which your To Do Application will live. Go ahead and, from the command line, create a new directory called "app_todo" and navigate into it:
                pre
                    code #bash&#10&#10mkdir app_todo && cd app_todo
                p From here you'll want to make three files, index.html, styles.css, and script.js:
                pre
                    code #bash&#10&#10touch index.html styles.css script.js
                p Now open up index.html in your text editor of choice and enter the following:
                pre
                    code &lt!DOCTYPE html&gt&#10&lthtml lang="en"&gt&#10  &lthead&gt&#10    &lttitle&gtApp ToDo&lt/title&gt&#10    &ltmeta charset="UTF-8" /&gt&#10    &ltmeta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1" /&gt&#10    &ltmeta name="description" content="A Basic ToDo Application" /&gt&#10    &ltlink type="text/css" href="./styles.css" rel="stylesheet" /&gt&#10  &lt/head&gt&#10  &ltbody&gt&#10    &ltmain&gt&#10      &lth1&gtApp ToDo&lt/h1&gt&#10    &lt/main&gt&#10  &lt/body&gt&#10  &ltscript type="text/javascript" src="./script.js" default defer&gt&lt/script&gt&#10&lt/html&gt&#10
                p As you can see, we are directly sourcing our styles.css and script.js files directly within our HTML. Let's set up some sane defaults in our styles.css file now:
                pre
                    code /*styles.css*/&#10&#10*,&#10*::before,&#10*::after {&#10  box-sizing: border-box;&#10}&#10&#10html {&#10  color-scheme: light dark;&#10}&#10&#10body {&#10  font-family: system-ui;&#10  font-size: 1.125rem;&#10  line-height: 1.5;&#10}&#10&#10main {&#10  width: min(70ch, 100% - 4rem);&#10  margin-inline: auto;&#10}&#10&#10img,&#10svg,&#10video {&#10  max-width: 100%;&#10  display: block;&#10}&#10&#10input,&#10textarea {&#10  min-width: 0;&#10}
                p Great! Now that we have that set up, let's lastly just put a simple log to the console in our script.js file to test that we set everything up properly:
                pre
                    code //script.js&#10&#10console.log("Hello World!");
                p Once you've finished, go ahead and use live-server (either from the <a class="inline-link" aria-label="a link to the live-server github repository" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" role="link" href="https://github.com/tapio/live-server">command line</a> or from within VSCode using the <a class="inline-link" aria-label="a link to the visualstudio marketplace's live server extension" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" role="link" href="https://marketplace.visualstudio.com/items?itemName=ritwickdey.LiveServer">the extension</a>) to start your development server. I personally use the command line to do so from within my project directory like so:
                pre
                    code #bash&#10&#10live-server .
                p This should automatically open up your browser on your localhost and show you the basic webpage you've just created with these three files. Open up your devtools as well once the browser is open by hitting the F12 key. If all is configured properly, you should see your html page with some very basic CSS stylings (from the styles.css file) and in your developer's console page, you should see the "Hello World!" message (from the scripts.js file). Your browser/devtools setup should look something like this:

                figure
                    img.img-image(src="../assets/images/screenshots/all_together_ss_01.webp" alt="a screenshot image showing our rendered html page" title="a screenshot of the rendered html page" cite="author screenshot" loading="lazy")
                figcaption The HTML Page Rendered By Live Server
                p Looks Good! Let's now start by centering our <code class="inline-code">h1</code> tag within a <code class="inline-code">div</code> tag with the class of <code class="inline-code">form-container</code>:
                pre
                    code   &ltbody&gt&#10    &ltmain&gt&#10      <b>&ltdiv class="form-container"&gt</b>&#10        &lth1&gtApp ToDo&lt/h1&gt&#10      <b>&lt/div&gt</b>&#10    &lt/main&gt&#10  &lt/body&gt
                p Adding "container" divs and spans to encapsulate other HTML elements is a common practice to apply styles to all elements within said container or, as you'll see below, directly to specific elements within that container. Let's now adjust our CSS to center our <code class="inline-code">form-container</code> div, and the <code class="inline-code">h1</code> tag within it.
                pre
                    code /*styles.css*/&#10&#10input,&#10textrea {&#10  min-width: 0;&#10}&#10&#10<b>.form-container {&#10  display: flex;&#10  flex-direction: column;&#10  justify-content: center;&#10  align-items: center;&#10}&#10&#10.form-container > h1 {&#10  margin: 1em auto -0.0125em auto;&#10  text-align: center;&#10}</b>
                p Now if we look at our updated HTML in our browser, we should see that our header "App ToDo" is indeed centered:
                figure
                    img.img-image(src="../assets/images/screenshots/all_together_ss_02.webp" alt="a screenshot of our HTML page with centered h1" title="a screenshot of our HTML page with centered h1" cite="author screenshot" loading="lazy")
                figcaption Our <code class="inline-code">h1</code> Tag Centered
                p In the interest of keeping this article concise, and to focus mainly on the logic of the JavaScript that we will implement, I'll not spend time on documenting the CSS aspects of this project. Please feel free to take a look at MDN's article on <a class="inline-link" aria-label="a link to MDN's article on centering an HTML element" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" role="link" href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/Layout_cookbook/Center_an_element">Centering An Element</a> should you be curious on how the above CSS works.
                p In order to create a series of todos, we'll need a way for the user to enter a todo, adding it to a list, with the result being that it renders nicely on our page. Let's first establish a <code class="inline-code">form</code> with an <code class="inline-code">input</code> field as well as a submit <code class="inline-code">button</code> for them to utilize to establish a todo:
                h2 HTML Forms
                p Forms in HTML are one of the few ways we can grab specific data from the user of our application. There is much to discuss when it comes to HTML forms and the various aspects to how to properly implement them in web applications, but as this is an introductory article, I'll forego most of that for now and simply dive into the basics. Here is how we can establish a basic HTML form below our <code class="inline-code">h1</code> tag:
                pre
                    code   &ltbody&gt&#10    &ltmain&gt&#10      &ltdiv class="form-container"&gt&#10        &lth1&gtApp ToDo&lt/h1&gt&#10        <b>&ltform id="todo-form-container"&gt&#10          &ltlabel class="todo-label" for="todo-input"&gtEnter A Todo:&lt/label&gt&#10          &ltinput&#10            type="text"&#10            name="todo-form"&#10            placeholder="Todo Item"&#10            minlength="1"&#10            maxlength="18"&#10            class="todo-input"&#10            id="todo-input"&#10          /&gt&#10        &lt/form&gt&#10        &ltinput type="submit" value="Add Todo" class="todo-button" id="add-todo-btn" /&gt&#10</b>      &lt/div&gt&#10    &lt/main&gt&#10  &lt/body&gt
                p There is a lot going on even in this simple form. The <code class="inline-code">label</code> tag provides us, the developer, with an easy way to establish a connection between our <code class="inline-code">input</code> tag using the <code class="inline-code">for</code> attribute. By inputting <em>"todo-input"</em> in the <code class="inline-code">label</code>'s <code class="inline-code">for</code> attribute, as well as in the <code class="inline-code">input</code>'s <code class="inline-code">id</code> attribute, creating an implicit relationship between the two HTML elements. 
                p The other attributes present within the <code class="inline-code">input</code> tag are somewhat self explanatory, but if you wish to explore further, I recommend taking a look at MDN's article on the <a class="inline-link" aria-label="A Link To MDN's Article On HTML Forms" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" role="link" href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Element/form">form element</a>.
                p At this point, our HTML form should render via live-server in our web browser like so:
                figure
                    img.img-image(src="../assets/images/screenshots/all_together_ss_03.webp" alt="An image of our new HTML form" title="An image of our new HTML form" cite="author screenshot" loading="lazy")
                figcaption Our HTML Form Is Now Rendered
                p Let's take a moment to return to our CSS to style our form a bit, give each element a bit of breathing room, and center these elements as well. Here is the relevant CSS:
                pre
                    code /*styles.css*/&#10&#10.form-container > h1 {&#10  margin: 1em auto -0.0125em auto;&#10  text-align: center;&#10}&#10&#10<b>.todo-label,&#10.todo-input,&#10.todo-button {&#10  display: flex;&#10  justify-content: center;&#10  align-items: center;&#10  flex-direction: column;&#10  margin: 1em auto 0.5em auto;&#10  font-weight: 500;&#10}&#10&#10.todo-input {&#10  padding: 0.25em;&#10  font-size: 1em;&#10  text-align: center;&#10  line-height: 1.5;&#10  border: 2px solid #000;&#10  border-radius: 5px;&#10  width: 20px;&#10  max-width: 80vw;&#10}&#10&#10.todo-button {&#10  padding: 0.25em 0.5em;&#10  font-size: 0.9em;&#10  line-height: 1.5;&#10  background-color: #fff;&#10}&#10&#10todo-button:hover {&#10  scale: 1.1;&#10}</b>
                p This CSS should now center our form, if we return to view our HTML in the browser, this should be reflected like so:
                figure
                    img.img-image(src="../assets/images/screenshots/all_together_ss_04.webp" alt="A ScreenShot Of Our HTML Page With The Form Centered" title="A ScreenShot Of Our HTML Page With The Form Centered" cite="author screenshot" loading="lazy")
                figcaption Our Form Is Now Centered And Styled
                p Let's now hook up our form to JavaScript events. We'll be starting small, simply making sure our interactions with our forms are <em>"seen"</em> by our JavaScript file. Remove our <code class="inline-code">console.log("Hello World!");</code> from our <code class="inline-code">script.js</code> file and replace it with this:
                pre
                    code //script.js&#10&#10console.log("Hello World!"); // Delete this line&#10&#10<b>const todoForm = document.getElementById("todo-form-container");&#10const todoBtn = document.getElementById("add-todo-btn");&#10const todoInput = document.getElementById("todo-input");&#10&#10&#10function handleSubmit(event) {&#10  event.preventDefault();&#10  console.log("handleSubmit function invoked!");&#10}&#10&#10function main() {&#10  todoForm.addEventListener("submit", handleSubmit);&#10  todoBtn.addEventListener("click", handleSubmit);&#10}&#10&#10main();</b>
                p Before explaining the above code, let's first test it in our browser to ensure it's working as expected. After inputting this code into our <code class="inline-code">script.js</code> file, we can return to our HTML page in the browser and interact with the form by typing in some text and hitting the <em>Enter</em> key. We also can click on our <em>Add Todo</em> button. Once either event is fired by our interaction with the webpage, the text <em>"handleSubmit function invoked!"</em> should be logged to the developer console.
                figure
                    img.img-image(src="../assets/images/gifs/all_together_01.gif" alt="A Gif Screenshot demonstrating that the form interacts via javascript" title="A Gif Screenshot demonstrating that the form interacts via javascript" cite="author screenshot" loading="lazy")
                figcaption Form Interactions Fire JavaScript Events
                p This is the first time in our tutorial series on these tools that I have now demonstrated how JavaScript is interacting with the Document Object Model(the DOM). In our JavaScript above, when we declare the variable <code class="inline-code">todoForm</code> like so:
                pre
                    code //script.js&#10&#10<b>const todoForm = document.getElementById("todo-form-container");</b>
                p We are instantiating a <em>reference</em> to the HTML element that we assigned an id called <code class="inline-code">todo-form-container</code> to. This refers specifically to this piece of HTML code:
                pre
                    code &ltform <b>id="todo-form-container"</b>&gt&#10  &ltlabel class="todo-label" for="todo-input"&gtEnter A Todo:&lt/label&gt&#10  &ltinput&#10    type="text"&#10    name="todo-form"&#10    placeholder="Todo Item"&#10    minlength="1"&#10    maxlength="18"&#10    class="todo-input"&#10    id="todo-input"&#10  /&gt&#10&lt/form&gt&#10&ltinput type="submit" value="Add Todo" class="todo-button" id="add-todo-btn" /&gt
                p We also grab references to our <code class="inline-code">add-todo-btn</code> and also our <code class="inline-code">todo-input</code>:
                pre
                    code //script.js&#10&#10const todoForm = document.getElementById("todo-form-container");&#10<b>const todoBtn = document.getElementById("add-todo-btn");&#10const todoInput = document.getElementById("todo-input");</b>
                p In our HTML, we can find references to these ids within the same markup example:
                pre
                    code &ltform id="todo-form-container"&gt&#10  &ltlabel class="todo-label" for="todo-input"&gtEnter A Todo:&lt/label&gt&#10  &ltinput&#10    type="text"&#10    name="todo-form"&#10    placeholder="Todo Item"&#10    minlength="1"&#10    maxlength="18"&#10    class="todo-input"&#10    <b>id="todo-input"</b>&#10  /&gt&#10&lt/form&gt&#10&ltinput type="submit" value="Add Todo" class="todo-button" <b>id="add-todo-btn"</b> /&gt
                p We then establish a <code class="inline-code">main</code> function. This is a common convention in not just JavaScript, but in many programming paradigms, where a final main <em>routine</em> is establisehd and, in some cases, invoked (as is seen on the last line of the <code class="inline-code">script.js</code> file). Usually the <code class="inline-code">main</code> function calls other <em>"helper"</em> functions within the file. While technically these invocations could occur in the global namespace of our program, it is a common convention and good practice to encapsulate our JavaScript in this fashion as it limits the declaration of global variables and is more readable overall.
                p Currently within our <code class="inline-code">main</code> functin, we grab our <code class="inline-code">todoForm</code> and <code class="inline-code">todoBtn</code> variables. Again, these are pulled from our references to the Document Object Model. These references themselves have various properties and methods that we can reference in order to program interactivity with our HTML elements. Inputs like the one we have created of type <em>"text"</em> have a <em>"submit"</em> event that we can <em>"listen"</em> to and initialize scripted events to occur. Similarly, our input of type <em>"text"</em> has a <em>"click"</em> event that we can hook into and "listen" for. Hence our <code class="inline-code">main</code> function invokes two <em>"addEventListener"</em> calls like so:
                pre
                    code //script.js&#10&#10function main() {&#10  todoForm.addEventListener("submit", handleSubmit);&#10  todoBtn.addEventListener("click", handleSubmit);&#10}
                p We then <em>"tell"</em> the DOM to add an <em>"event listener"</em> to our respective HTML input elements and associate that listener with a helper function called <code class="inline-code">handleSubmit</code>. Note that both events fire off the <code class="inline-code">handleSubmit</code> function. We could have fired off separate functions for each, but whether the user hits the <em>enter</em> key <em>or</em> clicks the <em>"Add Todo"</em> button, we want the same result (to register the creation of a new todo item).
                p The <code class="inline-code">handleSubmit</code> function is then invoked any time that the <em>"submit"</em> or the <em>"click"</em> events occur. In investigating our <code class="inline-code">handleSubmit</code> function, we find that it takes a <code class="inline-code">event</code> argument. This is needed in order to prevent the Browser's native actions when either the <em>"submit"</em> or <em>"click"</em> events occur. While a bit strange, it is a common practice in front end web development to circumvent the default behavior of these events using the <code class="inline-code">preventDefault</code> method:
                pre
                    code //script.js&#10&#10function handleSubmit(<b>event</b>) {&#10  <b>event.preventDefault();</b>&#10  console.log("handleSubmit function invoked!");&#10}
                p Lastly we then have our code we wish to invoke whenever the <code class="inline-code">handleSubmit</code> function is invoked. This, for the time being, is simply to log to the console the phrase "handleSubmit function invoked". We will now implement the logic to add a todo item, and have it render on our HTML page.
                h2 Adding Todos
                p Firstly we'll need to establish a JavaScript array to hold our todo items in memory. Once this is established, we'll then need to populate this array with our todo string whenever we hit the <em>"Enter"</em> button or click the <em>"Add Todo"</em> button. Finally, every time this event occurs, the array is rendered back to the HTML page in the form of an unordered list. Let's first establish the unordered list in our HTML file. Because this list will be blank at first, we'll simply leave it as a <code class="inline-code">ul</code> element for now:
                pre
                    code &ltinput type="submit" value="Add Todo" class="todo-button" <b>id="add-todo-btn"</b> /&gt&#10<b>&ltul id="todo-list"&gt&lt/ul&gt</b>
                p Let's take a brief moment to stylize our unordered list. Specifically, we'll be targeting any <code class="inline-code">li</code> elements that are created, that way they are somewhat readable when generated and rendered:
                pre
                    code /*styles.css*/&#10&#10.todo-button:hover {&#10  scale: 1.1;&#10}&#10&#10<b>.form-container > #todo-list {&#10  list-style: none;&#10  width: 100%;&#10  max-width: 18em;&#10  padding: 0;&#10}&#10&#10#todo-list > li {&#10  margin: 0.75em 0;&#10  padding: 0.25em;&#10  border-bottom: 2px solid #000;&#10  font-weight: 500;&#10}</b>
                p We'll now create an array called <code class="inline-code">myTodos</code>. For now, this array will live within the global scope of our program, but towards the end of this article, I will point you to a Github repository that will hold a more advanced form of this script for your reference with somewhat better practices involved in its execution. Start a new <code class="inline-code">myTodos</code> array at the tope of your <code class="inline-code">script.js</code> file. We'll also instantiate a reference to our <code class="inline-code">todo-list</code> as well:
                pre 
                    code //script.js&#10&#10const todoInput = document.getElementById("todo-input");&#10<b>const todoList = document.getElementById("todo-list");&#10const myTodos = [];</b>
                p Next we'll add the logic that will actually render our todos to the HTML document. Input the following code to the <code class="inline-code">handleSubmit</code> function:
                pre 
                    code //script.js&#10&#10function handleSubmit(event) {&#10  event.preventDefault();&#10  <b>todoList.innerHTML = "";&#10  myTodos.unshift(todoInput.value);&#10  for (let i = 0; i &lt myTodos.length; i++) {&#10    const newTodo = document.createElement("li");&#10    newTodo.textContent = myTodos[i];&#10    todoList.appendChild(newTodo);&#10  }&#10  todoInput.value = "";</b>&#10}
                p For the new developer, this can be a bit confusing. We'll break it down, don't worry, but first let's take a look at our HTML page and test our Todo App first:
                figure
                    img.img-image(src="../assets/images/gifs/all_together_02.gif" alt="A Screenshot gif demonstrating our working todo application" title="A Screenshot gif demonstrating our working todo application" cite="author screenshot" loading="lazy")
                figcaption Our Todo Application Works!
                p Excellent! Now that we have confirmed everything is working as expected, what exactly did we do? This bit of logic introduces a few new concepts, so let's break it down. The first new line we added to our <code class="inline-code">handleSubmit</code> function shows us accessing our <code class="inline-code">todoList</code>'s <code class="inline-code">innerHTML</code> property:
                pre 
                    code //script.js&#10&#10function handleSubmit(event) {&#10  event.preventDefault();&#10  <b>todoList.innerHTML = "";</b>&#10  ...
                p This is simply clearing out our unordered list, setting it's <code class="inline-code">innerHTML</code> back to being empty. Recall our related HTML code?:
